value.value: An acquired coagulation disorder characterized by the partial or complete absence of factor VIII activity in the blood.
A non-neoplastic or neoplastic disorder that affects the lymph nodes.
An abscess that is located in the spleen.
Trauma to the ear.
Trauma to the nose.

label.value: Malignant Neoplasm of the Lower Third of the Esophagus

value.value: A primary or metastatic malignant neoplasm involving the lower third segment of the esophagus.
A traumatic break in one of the bones in the rib cage that does not involve a break in the adjacent skin.
A traumatic break in one of the bones in the rib cage  that involves a break in the adjacent skin.
A traumatic break in one or more of the bones comprising the bony structure of the pelvis that does not involve a break in the adjacent skin.
A traumatic break in one or more of the bones comprising the bony structure of the pelvis that involves a break in the adjacent skin..
A traumatic break in one or more of the metacarpal bones.

label.value: Closed Fracture of Shaft of Metacarpal Bone

value.value: A traumatic break in the diaphysis of the metacarpal bone that does not involve a break in the adjacent skin.

label.value: Closed Fracture of Neck of Metacarpal Bone

value.value: A traumatic break in the area of the metacarpal bone located between the diaphysis and the distal metaphysis that does not involve a break in the adjacent skin.

label.value: Open Fracture of Shaft of Metacarpal Bone

value.value: A traumatic break in the diaphysis of the metacarpal bone that involves a break in the adjacent skin.

label.value: Open Fracture of Neck of Metacarpal Bone

value.value: A traumatic break in the area of the metacarpal bone located between the diaphysis and the distal metaphysis that involves a break in the adjacent skin.
A traumatic injury to the axilla resulting from exposure to caustic chemicals, extreme heat, extreme cold, or excessive radiation.
A primary or metastatic malignant neoplasm involving the ampulla of Vater.

Pneumonia caused by cytomegalovirus.  Most humans are exposed to cytomegalovirus.  Healthy individuals do not develop signs and symptoms of infection.  Patients with weakened immune system (e.g., AIDS patients, cancer patients who are being treated with chemotherapy, and patients who have received bone marrow or solid organ transplants) develop signs and symptoms of infection.  They include cough, shortness of breath, fatigue, malaise, fever, muscle and joint pain, and excessive sweating.

Fungal pneumonia caused by inhalation of particles of Cryptococcus.  It usually occurs in immunocompromised patients such as persons with AIDS, transplant recipients, patients receiving cytotoxic chemotherapy, and patients with hematologic malignancies.  It is rare in immunocompetent individuals.  Signs and symptoms include fever, cough, and dyspnea.
A bladder infection that occurs as a manifetation of a systemic infection with one or more species of the parasitic worms of the Schistosoma type; this can progress to bladder cancer in time.
Infection by Ancylostoma ceylanicum.
Cycles of fever with intervening periods of normothermia.
A term used for any state of depression that is not psychotic.
A primary or metastatic malignant neoplasm involving the retroperitoneum.  The vast majority of cases are carcinomas, lymphomas, or sarcomas.

A neoplasm that affects the bone marrow. It may arise in the bone marrow (e.g., myeloid leukemia) or may involve the bone marrow as a secondary, metastatic tumor (e.g., metastatic carcinoma to the bone marrow).
A radiologic finding indicating the presence of bone destruction that results from the spread of cancer to the bone(s).
Acute infection of the bile ducts caused by bacteria ascending from the small intestine.
A bacterial infection that is transmitted from animals to people.
Gastroenteritis resulting from a viral infection.
Traumatic compression of the body or a part of the body.
Congenital absence of the trachea.
An abnormal, epithelial-lined connection between an artery and vein that is present at the time of birth.
A primary or metastatic malignant neoplasm involving the peritoneum. Representative examples include carcinoma and malignant mesothelioma.
A morphologic finding indicating a change in a tissue due to vascular injury or leakage.

A morphologic finding indicating the presence of Mallory bodies in the liver parenchyma.  Mallory bodies are eosinophilic cytoplasmic inclusions in the hepatocytes.  They contain filaments and are present in the liver parenchyma of patients with various liver disorders including alcoholic liver disease, Wilson disease, and primary biliary cirrhosis.
An antiquated term referring to large cell lymphomas.
Physical and psychological dependence on hallucinogenics, which is associated with a pattern of continuous use.
Physical and psychological dependence on hallucinogenics, which is associated with a pattern of episodic use.
Physical and psychological dependence on the drug cannabis, which is associated with a pattern of continuous use.
Physical and psychological dependence on the drug cannabis, which is associated with a pattern of episodic use.
Physical or psychological dependence on the drug cocaine which is associated with a pattern of continuous use.
Physical and psychological dependence on the drug cocaine, which is associated with a pattern of episodic use.
A malignant neoplasm affecting the spleen. Representative examples include leukemias, lymphomas, and sarcomas.

label.value: Respiratory Malfunction Arising from Mental Factor

value.value: A respiratory malfunction for which mental factors play a causative role.
